Safety & Ladder Certification
Master the fundamentals of ladder safety — the non-negotiables that protect you, your team, and your customers every single day.
🦺
🎯 Required: 80% to pass ⏱️ ~15 min 📄 From company training deck
📊 From: Residential Window Cleaning Training Deck — Slide 4

Safety & Ladder Setup

🪜 4:1 Ladder Ratio

1 foot out for every 4 feet of height. No guessing. Measure it visually every time.

✋ 3 Points of Contact

Two hands & 1 foot — OR — 2 feet and 1 hand. At all times while climbing.

🔍 Ladder Inspection Before Climb

  • Check Pins, Locks, Bonnet, Levelers
  • Confirm base stability before leaving the ground

🏔️ Roof Transitions

  • Move slowly
  • Maintain stability
  • Never rush ladder-to-roof transitions
📖

In-Depth: The 4:1 Ladder Rule

The 4:1 rule is the industry-standard angle for safe ladder placement. For every 4 feet of working height, the base of the ladder must be 1 foot away from the wall or surface.

Example: If your ladder extends 16 feet up to a window, the base must be placed 4 feet away from the house. This gives you approximately a 75-degree angle — stable and safe.
Ladder HeightBase Distance from WallApprox. Angle
8 ft2 ft75°
12 ft3 ft75°
16 ft4 ft75°
20 ft5 ft75°
24 ft6 ft75°
🔍

Pre-Climb Ladder Inspection Checklist

Before you climb any ladder, every time, inspect these five areas:

  • Pins & Locks: All extension locks engaged and locked. Do not climb if any lock feels loose or doesn't click.
  • Bonnet (Top Cap): The plastic cap at the top of the ladder must be intact. Never use a ladder with a cracked or missing bonnet.
  • Levelers: If your ladder has adjustable leg levelers, ensure they are locked in place and both feet sit firmly on the ground.
  • Rungs: Visually inspect each rung for bends, cracks, or slippery surfaces. Never use a damaged ladder — tag it and remove it from service.
  • Base stability: Rock the base gently before climbing. If it shifts, re-position it before going up.
⚠️ Non-Negotiable: A damaged ladder is never "good enough for just one job." Remove it from service immediately and report it to your supervisor.
🏔️

Roof Transitions

Transitioning from a ladder to a roof (and back) is one of the most dangerous moments in window cleaning. The risk is highest when you rush.

  1. Ensure the ladder extends at least 3 rungs above the roofline before stepping off.
  2. Keep both hands on the ladder until both feet are planted firmly on the roof.
  3. Step onto a stable surface — avoid wet shingles, moss, or crumbling edges.
  4. Move slowly and deliberately. No sudden movements.
  5. When returning to the ladder, face the ladder, not away from it.
  6. Never carry tools in your hands during a transition — use a belt or tool holder.
💡 Rule of Thumb: If you feel rushed, stop. Take 10 seconds to breathe and set up properly. A fall takes a fraction of a second. Safety takes 10 seconds.
⛑️

Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)

✅ Always Required

  • Non-slip footwear (closed toe)
  • Gloves when using chemicals
  • Safety glasses when scraping
  • Charged phone on your person

✅ Situational PPE

  • Hard hat near overhead hazards
  • Knee pads for ground-level exterior work
  • Safety harness for steep roof access
  • Hi-vis vest near traffic areas
⚠️ Never work on a ladder in: Wind gusts over 25 mph, active lightning storms, or icy / frost-covered conditions. Reschedule the job — no exceptions.

Blade & Rubber Care

The squeegee blade is the most critical — and most neglected — part of the kit. A damaged blade cannot produce clean glass, period.

  1. Run your fingernail along the rubber edge before every job — feel for nicks or cuts.
  2. Rinse the blade with clean water after each window to prevent soap buildup.
  3. Flip the blade to use the other edge when one side becomes worn.
  4. Replace blades every 1–2 weeks under daily use, or immediately after any damage.
  5. Store squeegees rubber-side up or hanging — never resting flat on the blade edge.
💡 Fresh Rubber = Clean Glass. Don't cheap out on blades. A pack of replacement rubbers costs a few dollars. A callback to a customer over streaks costs your reputation.
🧪

Cleaning Solution Basics

ConditionSoap (pumps)Notes
Normal / Light soil1 – 1.5 pumpsStandard residential — most jobs
Heavy soil / Construction2 – 2.5 pumpsMore agitation needed for built-up grime
Hot / fast-dry weather1 – 1.5 pumps + 2 tbsp white vinegarVinegar slows evaporation, reduces streaks

❄️ Cold Weather — Methanol Ratios

⚠️ Use Methanol only — not rubbing alcohol. Methanol is the correct product for freeze prevention in professional window cleaning solutions.
Temperature RangeMethanolWaterRatio
20°F – 32°F1 part4 parts1:4
0°F – 19°F2 parts2 parts2:2 (1:1)
💡 Methanol Safety: Methanol is flammable and toxic — handle with gloves and keep away from heat sources. Never store in an unmarked container. Always mix outdoors or in a well-ventilated area.
⚠️ Add soap AFTER water to prevent excessive suds. The solution should feel slightly slippery — not foamy.
🚐

Job Prep & Van Setup

Zero wasted movement on the job starts in the van. A disorganized van means multiple trips, delays, and a sloppy first impression on the driveway.

  • All tools organized and accessible by category (ladders, cleaning tools, PPE)
  • Fresh blade installed on squeegee before arrival
  • Bucket rinsed and ready — not holding old solution from yesterday
  • Drop cloths folded and at the front of the van for quick access
  • Shoe covers stocked and within reach at the van door
  • Van parked on the street — not blocking the customer's driveway

Module 3 of 5
Exterior Cleaning Process
Screens, glass, frames — in the right order, every time. The top-down workflow is your system for a flawless exterior finish.
🏠
🎯 Required: 80% to pass ⏱️ ~15 min
📊 From: Residential Window Cleaning Training Deck — Slide 6

Exterior Cleaning Process

👁️ Exterior Walkthrough First

  • Confirm window count, identify problem glass
  • Locate water source
  • Plan ladder placement

🪟 Screen Removal & Staging

  • Remove screens completely
  • Stage by level or side of home
  • Set up wash & dry area before cleaning glass

⬇️ Top-Down Cleaning Workflow

  • Start at the highest point
  • Clean glass → Detail Frames → Move Down
  • No backtracking. Ever.
👁️

The Property Walkthrough

Always do a full exterior walkthrough before you set up a single piece of equipment. This is where you prevent problems before they happen.

  1. Walk the entire property with the client if possible. Point out any pre-existing damage — cracked glass, broken frames, damaged seals — before you touch anything.
  2. Count the windows and note any unusual types (arched, divided light, sealed units).
  3. Identify your water source. Know where the hose bib is before you need it.
  4. Plan all ladder placements. Note any soft ground, buried irrigation, overhead lines, or other hazards.
  5. Identify staining or problem glass that may require special treatment or a waiver.
⚠️ Waivers: Any scraping or specialty treatment on problem glass (hard water staining, paint, etc.) requires a signed client waiver before you start. This protects you and the company.
🪟

Screen Removal & Staging Process

📋 Removal Rules

  • Remove every screen before touching the glass
  • Note any screens that are bent, torn, or missing — report to client
  • Handle screens by the frame, not the mesh

📦 Staging Rules

  • Stage by level AND side of home (e.g., "North upstairs")
  • Lean screens against the house — never flat on the ground
  • Set up your screen wash & rinse area before cleaning any glass
💡 Screen System: A simple labeling system (masking tape + marker on the frame edge) saves enormous time at re-installation. Every screen back in the right spot, every time.
⬇️

Top-Down Workflow — Step by Step

The top-down rule is absolute. Dirty water always flows down. If you clean a lower window before an upper one, the upper window's rinse water will dirty the one you just finished.

  1. Start at the highest window on the highest floor of the house.
  2. Wet the entire pane with a loaded scrubber. Overlap the edges by 1 inch.
  3. Cut in: draw one clean horizontal strip across the top of the glass.
  4. Pull straight down, overlapping each stroke by ½ inch. Wipe the blade after every stroke.
  5. Detail the frame, sill, and edges with a microfiber cloth immediately after squeegeeing.
  6. Move to the next window on the same level. Never go back up.
  7. Complete the entire floor before moving down to the next.
ℹ️ No Backtracking. Once a level is complete, it stays complete. If you miss a window, note it and address it after finishing the current level — don't break your workflow to jump back up.
🔧

Squeegee Technique — The Straight Pull

IssueLikely CauseFix
StreaksWorn blade or too much soapReplace blade, reduce soap ratio
SqueakingToo little solution on glassRe-wet with scrubber
Water at edgesBlade not reaching frameUse smaller squeegee or detail with cloth
SmearingBlade dragging dryRe-wet the pane, smooth pressure
HazinessHard water baked inVinegar solution + 0000 steel wool
💡 Blade Angle: Keep the blade at 30–45 degrees to the glass. Too steep = skipping. Too flat = smearing. And wipe the blade with a clean cloth after every single stroke — this is the single most important habit a professional has.

Module 4 of 5
Interior Cleaning Process
Interior work demands a higher standard of care. You're in someone's home. Protect it, respect it, and leave it better than you found it.
🏠
🎯 Required: 80% to pass ⏱️ ~15 min
📊 From: Residential Window Cleaning Training Deck — Slide 7

Interior Cleaning Process

🚪 Home Entry Protocol

  • Introduce yourself
  • Confirm areas to be cleaned
  • Put on fresh shoe covers before stepping inside

🛡️ Protect the Customer's Home

  • Drop cloth at every work area
  • Tools placed on towel — never directly on floors or furniture

✨ Do ONE extra thing for every client

Clean a mirror, wipe a countertop, tidy a sill. Leave the room better than you found it.

🧹 Clean Glass → Detail Immediately

Mop → Squeegee → Edge Detail. Wipe frames, sill, sash & tracks before moving on.

🚪

Home Entry Protocol

  1. Knock or ring the doorbell. Greet the homeowner by name. Introduce yourself clearly.
  2. Put on fresh shoe covers at the door — before stepping one foot inside. Every. Single. Time.
  3. Do a quick verbal confirmation of which areas will be cleaned and any special requests.
  4. Ask about any obstacles or valuables you should be aware of.
  5. Secure any pets before bringing in any equipment.
ℹ️ Note: If bringing a ladder inside (for very high windows), the feet must be clean and covered. Wipe ladder feet with a damp cloth before entry and place rubber feet covers or lay a drop cloth beneath.
🛡️

Protecting the Interior

  • Lay a drop cloth at every window before setting up — flooring, carpet, and hardwood are all at risk from drips
  • All tools go on a towel — never directly on counters, floors, or furniture
  • Wring the scrubber more thoroughly for interior work — less water means less risk
  • Keep a dry microfiber on your shoulder at all times for instant drip response
  • Slide furniture away carefully — never drag. Return it to the exact position when done.
  • No fingerprints on glass, walls, or any surface that isn't being cleaned
⚠️ Zero Drips Policy: A single water drip on a hardwood floor or fine rug is a customer complaint waiting to happen. Control your water on interior work — it's the #1 cause of interior callbacks.
✅

Interior Cleaning Sequence

  1. Remove or slide obstacles. Identify window type and how it opens.
  2. Remove the screen and place it in a safe, organized location.
  3. Lay your drop cloth directly below the window.
  4. Wet the glass with a lightly wrung scrubber.
  5. Squeegee using your standard stroke technique.
  6. Detail immediately — wipe the frame, sill, sash, and tracks with a microfiber cloth before moving on.
  7. Pick up your drop cloth, check the floor for any drips, and return furniture.
  8. Do one extra thing. Wipe the window ledge, clean a nearby mirror, dust the sill. Small gestures create loyal customers.

Customer Service & Professionalism
Clean windows get you paid once. Exceptional service gets you paid forever. Your attitude, communication, and attention to detail are as important as your technique.
🤝
🎯 Required: 80% to pass ⏱️ ~15 min
📊 From: Residential Window Cleaning Training Deck — Slide 8 (Summary)

Training Summary

🦺 Safety & Ladder Setup

  • Proper 4:1 angle every time
  • 3 points of contact while climbing
  • Ladder inspected before leaving the ground

🛠️ Equipment & Job Prep

  • Tools staged before starting
  • Fresh rubber, clean water, organized belt
  • Van parked & workflow planned for zero wasted movement

🪟 Exterior Cleaning System

  • Walk the property first (with client)
  • Screens removed & staged correctly
  • Top-down workflow, no backtracking
  • Damage identified & shown to client — waivers signed before scraping

🏠 Interior Cleaning Process

  • Drop cloths & shoe covers always
  • Clean ladder feet before entering
  • Clean the floor after the windows
😊

First Impressions — Arriving at the Job

  • Arrive within your scheduled window. If you'll be late, call ahead — always.
  • Wear a clean, branded uniform or neat professional clothing. You represent the company.
  • Greet the customer by name. Smile. Introduce yourself.
  • Do a brief walk-around to identify concerns or special requests before you begin.
  • Never rush the introduction — 60 seconds of attentiveness sets the tone for the whole job.
💬

Communication During the Job

✅ Say This

  • "I noticed the seal on this double-pane is broken — just wanted to let you know before I continue."
  • "This staining is heavy. I can improve it significantly, but it may need a specialist treatment to fully resolve."
  • "Is there anything specific you'd like me to focus on today?"

❌ Avoid This

  • Promising results you can't guarantee
  • Saying "I didn't do that" defensively about pre-existing damage
  • Leaving without a final walk-through
  • Being on your phone during the job
✅

The Final Walk-Through

  1. Walk the customer through each area you cleaned before collecting payment.
  2. Point out anything noteworthy — a stubborn spot you treated, a screen you repaired, a condition you noticed.
  3. Ask: "Is there anything you'd like me to look at again?" This is professionalism, not weakness.
  4. Thank them by name and leave a business card.
  5. If they seem satisfied: "We'd really appreciate a Google review — it means the world to a small business."
💡 The $1,000 Mindset: Every loyal customer, with repeat visits and referrals, is worth well over $1,000 to this business over time. Treat every single one like it.
🔄

Handling Complaints

  1. Listen fully without interrupting or becoming defensive.
  2. Acknowledge: "I understand, and I appreciate you telling me."
  3. Assess the complaint in person — look at the issue directly rather than debating.
  4. Fix it on the spot if possible, or schedule a return visit immediately — same week.
  5. Follow up after resolution. A quick text or call shows you care about more than the payment.
